Brexit, and what comes next?
NEW YORK – It will take a long time for the United Kingdom, the European Union, and the world as a whole to digest the implications of the Brexit referendum led by the United Kingdom.
The deepest consequences will, of course, depend on the European Union's response to the UK's withdrawal.
Most people initially believed that the EU would not «cut the branch it was sitting on»: after all, a friendly divorce seems to be in everyone's interest.
But the divorce – as is often the case – could become complicated.
The commercial and economic integration benefits between the United Kingdom and the EU are mutual, and if the EU took seriously its belief that more economic integration is desirable, its leaders would seek to ensure that the links remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
However, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive tax avoidance schemes benefiting businesses in Luxembourg and now President of the European Commission, seems to be adopting a hard line: "Out means out," he declared.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be seen as the one who presided over the first stage of the EU's dissolution.
He argues that, in order to deter other countries from leaving, the EU must accept no compromise, offering the United Kingdom barely more than what is guaranteed by the World Trade Organization agreements.
In other words, the EU should not be kept united by the benefits it offers its members, which far exceed its costs.
The economic prosperity, sense of solidarity, and pride in being European are not enough, according to Juncker.
No, Europe must be maintained through threats, intimidation, and fear.
This position fails to take into account a lesson that is clearly evident, both in the Brexit vote and in the Republican primary elections in the United States: a large part of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the last four decades may have been good for the top 1%, but not for the rest of the population.
I had long predicted that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
This day has now arrived.
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens consider trade agreements to be the source of their misfortunes.
Although it is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
Today's trade agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of corporate interests but complete exclusion of ordinary citizens or workers.
As expected, the results were one-sided: the workers' negotiating position has weakened further, exacerbating the effects of legislation that reduces the weight of unions and employees' rights.
Although trade agreements have played a role in the creation of these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to tipping the political balance in favor of capital.
Intellectual property rules, for example, have increased the power of pharmaceutical companies to raise prices.
However, any increase in the market power of companies implies a de facto decline in real wages – an increase in inequalities that has become a characteristic of most advanced countries today.
In many sectors, industrial concentration is increasing – and so is market power.
The effects of stagnation and the decline in real wages have added to those of austerity, which has threatened cuts in public services that so many low- and middle-income workers rely on.
The economic uncertainty that results for workers, when combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for all, but especially for the former colonial powers.
And yet, although many would probably deny it, an increase in the supply of unskilled labor leads – as long as we are in the presence of normal downward-sloping demand curves – to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot fall, unemployment increases.
Ceci est surtout préoccupant dans les pays où une mauvaise gestion économique a déjà conduit à un niveau élevé de chômage global.
L'Europe, en particulier la zone euro, a été très mal gérée au cours des dernières décennies, au point que son taux de chômage moyen est dorénavant à deux chiffres.
La migration sans entrave en Europe signifie que les pays qui ont mieux réussi à réduire le chômage finiront de manière prévisible par accueillir plus que leur juste part de réfugiés.
Les travailleurs de ces pays supportent le coût des salaires déprimés et d’un chômage plus élevé, tandis que les employeurs bénéficient d'une main-d'œuvre meilleur marché.
Le fardeau des réfugiés, sans surprise, est supporté par les personnes qui sont le moins en mesure de le faire.
Of course, there are many speeches about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed benefits – social protection, education, healthcare etc. – to all its citizens, this may be the case.
But, for countries that provide a decent safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on wages and cuts in public services has been the erosion of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Households in the middle and working classes have not benefited from economic growth.
They understand that banks caused the 2008 crisis; but then they saw billions allocated to save the banks, and insignificant amounts to save their homes and jobs.
While the real (inflation-adjusted) median income for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, the anger of the electorate should come as no surprise.
Furthermore, politicians who promised change have not met expectations.
Ordinary citizens knew the system was unfair, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thereby losing the little trust they still had in the ability or willingness of traditional politicians to fix it.
This is also understandable: the new politicians shared the perspectives of those who had promised that globalization would be beneficial for everyone.
However, a vote of anger does not solve problems, and may instead lead to a political and economic situation that is even worse.
The same applies if one responds with anger to a vote.
Forgotten the past is a basic principle in economics.
On both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment could have done so little to address the concerns of many citizens.
Every government of the EU must now consider improving the well-being of ordinary citizens as its main objective.
Davantage d’idéologie néolibérale n’aidera pas.
Et nous devrions arrêter de confondre objectifs et moyens: par exemple, le libre-échange, s’il est bien géré, pourrait apporter une plus grande prospérité partagée; mais s’il est mal géré, il réduira certainement le niveau de vie de beaucoup – peut-être de la majorité – des citoyens.
Il existe des alternatives aux dispositions néolibérales actuelles qui peuvent créer une prospérité partagée, tout comme il existe des alternatives – comme l’accord de Partenariat transatlantique de commerce et d’investissement avec l’UE proposé par le président américain Barack Obama – qui causerait beaucoup plus de mal.
Le défi aujourd'hui est d'apprendre du passé, afin d’adopter les premières et d’éviter les secondes.
